  <h1>Types of Protected Activity and Retaliation</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Protected activity under Title VII</h2><p>Filing an EEOC charge; making an internal harassment or discrimination complaint (even an informal one); participating in an employer&rsquo;s investigation of another employee&rsquo;s complaint; testifying in a discrimination proceeding; opposing discriminatory practices (even without a formal complaint).</p>
  <h2>Protected activity under the FLSA</h2><p>Filing a wage claim with the Department of Labor; making an internal complaint about unpaid wages or overtime; participating in a DOL investigation; consulting an attorney about wage rights (in some jurisdictions); discussing wages with coworkers (also protected by the NLRA).</p>
  <h2>Protected activity under OSHA</h2><p>Reporting workplace safety hazards to OSHA; requesting an OSHA inspection; participating in an OSHA investigation; refusing to perform imminently dangerous work. The 30-day filing deadline makes prompt action critical.</p>
  <h2>Forms of retaliatory action</h2><p>Termination, demotion, reduction in pay or hours, schedule changes to less desirable shifts, removal from projects, increased workload without pay increase, heightened scrutiny and micromanagement, exclusion from meetings, negative performance reviews that diverge from prior evaluations, and constructive discharge.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-retaliation-claims-work">how retaliation claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
